description: More recently, if you will, it was June 30, 2018, a birthday present: A Jesse McCartney concert at iPlay in New Jersey, I was with my mom, I remember what I was wearing, my hairstyle, I can see where we were standing, the concertgoers around us, the lights, and he sang this song because he wrote it, and when I have one memory it brings on everything attached with that to previous Jesse memories, which brings on the nostalgic emotional aspect.
experience: I have always enjoyed Leona Lewis' voice, and I have been a fan of Jesse McCartney since DreamStreet, so I was 10 at that time.  Leona's version was always on or used in shows, but I never tired of it. Especially when I finally found it that Jesse wrote it, which wasn't too long after that. I always remember the different interviews that he would talk about his songwriting, and Bleeding Love being one of them. Then, when he had a version of him singing it, of course, I made it a part of my playlist. It really just encompasses a huge chunk of my life because of Jesse and the connection that song has to him. So it's a continuation.

association: I associate Train in general with my girl cousin who is two years older me, so about 10 or 11 and until now.
description: So the funny thing is because this song is by Train, it actually evoked an earlier memory from the early 2000s, around 2001 and 2002, because I was too caught up in that memory, I almost didn't click the button; my cousins from South Jersey would come up to stay with us for about a week in the summer. This time, it was my female cousin who is two years older than me and her younger brother who is one year younger than me, were at my house while my  mom was at work, her and I were in the stairway (the first landing) before we painted the walls and changed the carpet, the sun was shining a but through the blinds, the two of us still in our PJs, and we started singing Drops of Jupiter by Train because that summer, every time we turned on the radio, that song was on, so ultimately, it was always in our heads. Good times.
experience: It was always on the radio in 2009/2010. I just remembered being at a stop light in town, the exact street, early evening, and my mom and I were going to Target. They had songs that would just get in your head.

description: Just yesterday, while I was reading a short story on my phone in my bedroom, this gif popped up during it, and it was from this song, then all I could hear was this playing in my head; I was annoyed then and I was annoyed when I heard this song during the survey, so I kind of just sat there remembering how annoyed I was.
experience: I don't know why, but I always associate this song with the summer season for some reason. And literally, that's about as far as it goes for me.

association: In keeping with being a high school mentor, and a bit before that, one of the girls that I mentored was/still is a HUGE Justin Bieber fan, and it was played in random YouTube clips in short bursts. I was about 25-27.
description: It was Christmas 2017, and our small group of high school mentors (and my step-dad, because he and I were both mentors at church at the same time) had a karaoke/Ugly Christmas Sweater/Dinner gathering at coffee shop in Northern NJ; it was SOOO cold, but so warm in feeling and actual temperature in the cafe, it was quaint and cozy, and the company was one of my favorites ever, but during one of the karaoke songs, the two girls (yes, I remember their names, and what they looked like that night) chose Justin Bieber's Sorry, and the funny thing is, they were just excited to be singing the song and that it was on the list, I'm not even sure they remembered that we were all there with them.
experience: Well, as mentioned before, my mentee loves Justin Bieber so she's the first person I thought right after that specific memory.
